==Russian==

===Etymology===
The word was coined by [[:w:Strugatsky brothers|Strugatsky brothers]] for their novel "[[:w:Roadside Picnic|Roadside Picnic]]" (1972), as an allusion to [[:w:Rudyard Kipling|Rudyard Kipling]]'s character ''Stalky'' from "[[:w:Stalky & Co.|Stalky & Co.]]" stories. '''Сталки''' (stál-kee) was well remembered by Strugatskys since their childhood, when they read the stories in  Russian translation. In the "Roadside Picnic" '''сталкер''' was common nickname for men, engaged in illegal trade of prospecting and smuggling alien artifacts from the mysterious and dangerous "Zone".

===Noun===
'''сталкер''' {{m}}, {{p}} [[сталкеры]]

# [[stalker]] (''traditional translation, although not very accurate in meaning and connotations'')
# any person, whose occupation or activity is dangerously similar to those of characters from "Roadside Picnic".